# Query Wiki

## Goal
Answer the user's question by searching and synthesizing content from the {{config.project.name}} wiki. The wiki is a compiled knowledge base — the cross-references are already built, the contradictions are already flagged, and the synthesis reflects everything ingested. Your job is to navigate this compiled knowledge and give a precise, well-cited answer.

## Core Principle
Good answers can be filed back into the wiki as new pages. A comparison you create, an analysis you run, a connection you discover — these are valuable and should not disappear into chat history. Your explorations compound in the knowledge base just like ingested sources do.

<workflow>

<step n="1" goal="Parse and understand the question">
  <action>Identify what the user is asking: factual lookup, comparison, synthesis, exploration, or open-ended investigation</action>
  <action>Note any specific entities, concepts, or sources mentioned in the question</action>
  <action>Determine if this requires a single page lookup or multi-page synthesis</action>
</step>

<step n="2" goal="Locate relevant wiki pages">
  <action>Read `wiki/index.md` to identify potentially relevant pages — this is the primary navigation tool</action>
{{#if (includes config.workflows.tools "qmd")}}
  <action>Use `qmd query "{question}"` for semantic search across wiki pages — finds conceptually related content even when exact keywords don't match</action>
{{else}}
  <action>Use `.forge/tools/search.sh "{keywords}"` to find pages containing relevant terms</action>
{{/if}}
  <action>Compile a list of relevant pages to read in full</action>
  <action>Follow {{config.wiki.cross_ref_style}} links between pages to find connected content — the cross-references were built during ingestion precisely for this purpose</action>
</step>

<step n="3" goal="Gather evidence from wiki pages">
  <action>Read each relevant page in full</action>
  <action>Extract: direct answers, supporting evidence, contradictions, confidence levels</action>
  <action>Note the source backing for each piece of evidence — trace claims back through wiki pages to their original sources</action>
  <action>Track which pages contributed to the answer</action>
  <action>Pay attention to pages with `confidence: disputed` — present both sides rather than choosing one</action>
</step>

<step n="4" goal="Synthesize answer">
  <action>Compose a clear, structured answer to the user's question</action>
  <action>Cite specific wiki pages using {{config.wiki.cross_ref_style}} references for every factual claim</action>
  <action>Clearly separate known (wiki-backed) information from inferred or uncertain information</action>
  <action>If wiki pages conflict, present both perspectives with their evidence and note the contradiction</action>
  <action>Use headings and bullet points for readability in longer answers</action>
  <action>For comparison questions, build a structured table — this is often more useful than prose</action>
{{#if (includes config.workflows.outputs "marp")}}
  <action>If the user wants a presentation-ready answer, mention that `wforge-generate-slides` can turn wiki content into a Marp slide deck</action>
{{/if}}
</step>

<step n="5" goal="Compound the exploration back into the wiki">
  <critical>This is a key insight: your explorations should compound in the knowledge base, not disappear into chat history. Filing is delegated to the `wforge-file-answer` skill — there is one canonical filing path for the whole wiki, and this is it.</critical>
  <check if="the answer synthesized multiple pages into a novel comparison, analysis, or connection">
{{#if (eq config.workflows.ingestion_style "autonomous")}}
    <action>Maturity check: verify the synthesis drew from at least {{config.maturity.synthesis_pages_min}} wiki pages. If it drew from fewer, the wiki is too thin for reliable autonomous synthesis — offer filing to the user via `wforge-file-answer` and WAIT for confirmation instead of auto-filing</action>
    <action>If sufficient pages contributed: invoke `wforge-file-answer` directly with the answer payload — it will route to `wiki/comparisons/`, `wiki/concepts/`, or `wiki/entities/` by shape, create the page with proper frontmatter and bidirectional cross-references, update the index, and log the creation with `[AUTO]` prefix</action>
{{else}}
    <action>Offer to invoke `wforge-file-answer` with the answer payload. file-answer will route the page to `wiki/comparisons/`, `wiki/concepts/`, or `wiki/entities/` by shape and handle frontmatter, cross-linking, indexing, and logging</action>
    <action>If the user declines, do nothing — not every answer is worth filing, and file-answer also enforces a quality bar internally</action>
{{/if}}
  </check>
  <check if="the answer revealed knowledge gaps">
{{#if (eq config.workflows.ingestion_style "autonomous")}}
    <action>Automatically add the gaps to the Open Questions section of `wiki/overview.md` (or invoke `wforge-update-overview` for a full refresh if the wiki has shifted meaningfully)</action>
    <action>Log the additions with `[AUTO] query-gaps | added {count} open questions from query`</action>
{{else}}
    <action>Suggest specific sources or topics to ingest that would fill these gaps</action>
    <action>Note gaps as open questions — offer to add them to `wiki/overview.md` (or run `wforge-update-overview` for a full refresh)</action>
{{/if}}
  </check>
  <check if="the answer revealed a contradiction not previously flagged">
{{#if (eq config.workflows.ingestion_style "autonomous")}}
    <action>Automatically flag the contradiction on the relevant wiki pages with `confidence: disputed` and a WARNING callout documenting both positions</action>
    <action>Log the flagging with `[AUTO] query-contradiction | flagged dispute between {page A} and {page B}`</action>
    <action>Invoke `wforge-resolve-contradiction` to attempt reconciliation — supersession, annotation, or split, as appropriate</action>
{{else}}
    <action>Offer to flag it on the relevant wiki pages with `confidence: disputed`</action>
    <action>Suggest running `wforge-resolve-contradiction` to reconcile the conflicting claims, or `wforge-adversarial-review` to pressure-test them</action>
{{/if}}
  </check>
</step>

</workflow>
